Aliens in Cinema

The Data

The list of films and their release years was downloaded from this Wiki page. Metacritic, IMDB and Rotten Tomatoes scores were obtained using the wonderful The Open Movie Database. This is the raw .csv data:

df = read.csv('alien_data.csv')

Score distributions

Lets look at the score distributions for different sites:

library(tidyverse)
gather(df, Site, Score, c(Metacritic, Internet.Movie.Database, Rotten.Tomatoes)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=Score)) +
  facet_grid(Site ~ .) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), bins = 50, alpha=0.4) + 
  geom_density() +
  geom_vline(mapping=aes(xintercept=mean(Score)), size=1)

How about the distribution of the IMDB Votes? 
ggplot(data=df, mapping=aes(IMDB.Votes)) +
  geom_density()

Let’s now plot the top IMDB and the top Metacritic alien films together. First thing let’s check how many films ecen are scored by both sites:

(count(df) - select(df, Metacritic, Internet.Movie.Database) %>% filter(is.na(Metacritic) | is.na(Internet.Movie.Database)) %>% count)$n
## [1] 269

That’s only 47% off all the films, sad! Ok, now let’s do the plotting:

ggplot(data=df, mapping=aes(Metacritic, Internet.Movie.Database)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.6) +
  xlim(0,1) +
  ylim(0,1)

How about coloring points by number of their IMDB votes?

ggplot(data=df, mapping=aes(Metacritic, Internet.Movie.Database, color=IMDB.Votes)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.6) +
  xlim(0,1) +
  ylim(0,1)

Let’s see how rated are the most popular 90th centile films:

upperVotes = (df %>% summarise(x = quantile(IMDB.Votes, probs = 0.90, na.rm=T)))$x

ggplot(data=df, 
       mapping=aes(Metacritic, Internet.Movie.Database, 
       color=ifelse(IMDB.Votes > upperVotes, 'Yes', 'No'),
       alpha=ifelse(IMDB.Votes > upperVotes, 1.0, 0.9))) +
  geom_point() +
  xlim(0,1) +
  ylim(0,1) +
  labs(colour = 'Very popular')+ 
  guides(alpha = FALSE)

Clearly, most popular films on IMDB are better rated than less popular films. See how the spread of their ratings is much smaller on the IMDB axis than the Metacritic axis.

Let’s now focus on the top of the top, that is the films that are rated above 0.7 for both Metacritic and IMDB:

df %>%
  filter(Metacritic > 0.7 & Internet.Movie.Database > 0.7) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(Metacritic, Internet.Movie.Database),
         label=Title) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_label(aes(label=Title))
